# Using Dynatrace OpenPipeline by Grail for processing rules and metric extraction  
#
### Overview
___
#
Duration: 10 min
#
### Use Case
* Understand, how to use OpenPipeline to process, route, create metrics and enrich data ingested to Grail.
#
### What Youâ€™ll Learn Today 
#
1. Simulate ingest of data in the tenant using workflows and javascript.
2. Create DPL to extract important data to fields.
3. Create Pipeline with the DPL, use the log ingested via workflows to verify.
4. Create metric based on the DPL.
5. Create a Dynamic routing associated with the pipeline created.
6. Verify pipeline created and metric extraction is working.

#
Dynatrace Log Management and Analytics, powered by Grail, provides a unified approach to unlocking the value of log data in the Dynatrace platform. Hassle-free management of your log data lets you store petabytes of data without schemas, indexing, or rehydration. All of that data is usable at any time for any analytics task. Thanks to schema on-read and the Dynatrace Query Language, there's no need to decide what you want to query during data ingestion. Pick the retention period for your data that fits your business and compliance needs, whether debugging or audit.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
OpenPipeline is the Dynatrace data handling solution to seamlessly ingest and process data from different sources, at any scale, and in any format in the Dynatrace Platform.

### Use cases
* Configure ingestion and processing of different data types, such as logs and events, via a unified solution.
* Scala data management across teams by controlling access and targeted technologies.
* Ensure secure and compliant sensitive data handling.
* Enrich and contextualize data via customizable data processing.
* Optimize data quality and cost control.
#
With OpenPipeline, you can ingest data in the Dynatrace platform from a wide variety of formats and providers, through ingest sources. Data is then routed to pipelines for processing, and stored in Grail buckets.
#
![](https://dt-cdn.net/images/openpipeline-2500-87f73d19d1.png)


 Reference: [OpenPipeline](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/openpipeline-dataflow)

#### Step 2: Create DPL to extract important data to fields.
#
After you ingest some logs you can use a notebook, extract fields to get the DPL that you are going to use in your pipeline.
#
For the log ingested with the workflows, the following DPL should work to extract product and price:
#
` parse content, """'The price of the product' LD:product 'is $' DOUBLE:price"""`

#### Step 3: Create Pipeline with the DPL, use the log ingested via workflows to verify.
#
Prerequisites for OpenPipeline app:
`openpipeline:configurations:write` and `openpipeline:configurations:read` permissions
#
On the OpenPipeline app, we are going to start with the Pipelines section.
#
Once data is ingested and routed, OpenPipeline processing occurs in pipelines. Each pipeline contains a set of processing instructions (processors), that are executed in an ordered sequence of stages and define how you want Dynatrace to structure, separate, and store your data. After a record is processed, it's sent to storage and is available for further analysis.

By default data types are processed in dedicated built-in pipelines. You can create new custom pipelines to group processing and extraction by technology or team.
#
![](https://dt-cdn.net/images/stages-2497-7cb2c914ee.png)
#
When you create a pipeline, on the *Processing* Subsection you can create a processor using DQL, Add Fields, Rename Fields or Remove Fields.
#
In this case, you are going to use the DQL processor, you have to define the name, the matching condition, for this example can be based on the content `matchesPhrase(content,"The price of the product")` or the log.source `matchesPhrase(log.source,"/var/open/syslog")` and the DPL mentioned before. 
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
References: [OpenPipeline Processing](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/openpipeline-processing)
[Configure a processing pipeline](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/openpipeline-configure)

#### Step 4: Create metric based on the DPL.
#
To create a metric on the same pipeline, you are going to find a subsection called *Metric extraction*, in this section you have to configure the name, the matching condition (in this case the same as the processing rule), the metric key and the dimensions.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
[Create a metric in a pipeline](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/platform/openpipeline/use-cases/tutorial-log-processing-pipeline#openpipeline)

#### Step 5: Create a Dynamic routing associated with the pipeline created.
#
Finally, the last step is to configure in the `Dynamic Routing` section, the dynamic route associated to the pipeline created before, here you have to define the name, the matching condition and the target pipeline.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
[Create a dynamic route](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/openpipeline-configure#route)

#### Step 6: Verify pipeline created and metric extraction is working
#
To verify the Pipeline, you can go to the notebook and execute the following DQL, here you are going to find the log parsed by the procesing rule of the pipeline or you can search for the `dt.openpipeline.pipelines` fields where your are going to find the associated pipeline.
# 
``` 
fetch logs
| filter log.source == "/var/open/syslog" 
```
Also,you can search for the metric key ``log.open.price`` in the below "Explore Metrics" section

input.value: timeseries { avg(log.open.price), value.A = avg(log.open.price, scalar: true) }

## Wrap Up
___
#
Duration: 1
### Lab recap
#
Today we reviewed how the Dynatrace platform can be leveraged to provide via OpenPipeline the capabilities to process, metric extraction, data extraction, permission and storage using Dynatrace Log Analytics, Notebooks and DQL powered by Grail. 
#
Today you learned how to:
#
1. Simulate ingest of data in the tenant using workflows and javascript.
2. Create DPL to extract important data to fields.
3. Create Pipeline with the DPL, use the log ingested via workflows to verify.
4. Create metric based on the DPL.
5. Create a Dynamic routing associated with the pipeline created.
6. Verify pipeline created and metric extraction is working.
